<p class="pageheader">LDoN Mini Q&A #1
<hr noshade/></p>
<b>07-11-2004</b> - 
<B>Lepidus:</B> The much-anticipated dynamic dungeon system is one of the coolest features about Lost Dungeons. Do you think you could explain that feature a little more?
<P>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> An adventure starts with the gathering of your group. You'll get together and then find a Wayfarer camp. Talking to the Wayfarers reveals that they have a task that they would like you to complete. The Wayfarer estimates the ability of your group and asks you to complete a task that he believes is within your ability, but your group leader can ask for a harder task if your group is feeling brave.
<P>
As soon as you accept the task, a dungeon instance is created. This is a complete dungeon, with NPCs, objects, and everything. Only your group can enter this dungeon, and they can come and go as they wish for as long as the zone remains.
<P>
Once you have accepted the adventure, your group has a specified amount of time to get into the zone. Portals into the various zone themes are in old world zones, and the time given is more than enough to reach these portals. Once you enter the dungeon, you have a specific amount of time to complete your task. All of this information is available in the Adventure window (which any group member can open at any time using Alt-V).
<P>
As you travel these dungeons, you will notice that NPCs generally do not respawn. To achieve your goal you have to keep moving forward into the dungeon. Once you complete your adventure (or time runs out), the dungeon instance disappears. Any player characters or PC corpses are moved to the portal where they entered.
<P>
This allows us a lot of flexibility and control over what we present to the players. Knowing what level their group is, we can be much more certain that they face a challenge and that they are rewarded appropriately. Also, with each completed adventure a character earns points. They can save these points to purchase any item they are offered by the Wayfarer Merchant. This allows players to work towards a reward of their choosing.
<P>
<B>Lepidus:</B> Each expansion advanced the story of Norrath a little more. Specifically, what will Lost Dungeons do to advance it further? Will any of these story advancements have server wide implications?
<P>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> Well, a lot of the initial story has been revealed on our web site (www.lostdungeonsofnorrath.com). This tells you a bit about how the Wayfarers Brotherhood began. But there is a lot more lore tied into the dungeons, and you can only hear those stories as you travel the path of adventure in game.
<P>
<B>Lepidus:</B>Planes of Power required guilds to mass recruit due to encounters requiring upwards of 60-80 people. How will you prevent these guilds from breaking part with the 36 player limit for Lost Dungeons' Personal Raids?"
<P>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> It seems very unlikely that a strong guild would break up over any expansion. For many folks the return to smaller raid groups is very desirable. We won't be removing any of the existing raid content, so if the guild wants to go someplace in force, all of those options are still open to them. With a 70 member raid many people feel that their individual accomplishments are less important, and get more satisfaction from being a strong contributor in a smaller raid where the value of any individual member is more important.
<P>
If we look at that same question from a different angle, if you have 70 people in your guild, then you're 2 new people shy of running two of these raids at once. Are we "forcing" guilds to break up or get bigger? Also consider that we added the raid functionality to allow people from more than one guild to work together in a temporary grouping construct. Think of these raids as another option in what's become a complex layering of possible gaming options meant to cater to the broadest range of play styles possible. We're trying new things with LDoN. That doesn't mean that all future free zones and expansions will utilize the exact same logic or systems. 
<b><i>We would like to thank Alan for his time.</B></I>

